        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4267179966" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1443567135343586068">yep, i sure did read this whilst perched on a cemetery hill, just before dusk on halloween 🎃<br/><br/>although the autumnal imagery is beautiful, i wish this was a more atmospheric read. irving&apos;s writing is intensely descriptive, but he spends so much time on pies and pastries and ladies&apos; bosoms, where instead there could be more descriptions of the drowsy, enchanted hollow!<br/><br/>i do love the open ending. <a class='jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction'>(view spoiler)</a><span class='spoilerContainer' style='display: none'>[though i&apos;d seen a movie version as a kid, i couldn&apos;t remember ichabod&apos;s fate. and that&apos;s be</span></span>
  <span id="freeText1443567135343586068" style="display:none">yep, i sure did read this whilst perched on a cemetery hill, just before dusk on halloween 🎃<br /><br />although the autumnal imagery is beautiful, i wish this was a more atmospheric read. irving's writing is intensely descriptive, but he spends so much time on pies and pastries and ladies' bosoms, where instead there could be more descriptions of the drowsy, enchanted hollow!<br /><br />i do love the open ending. <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[though i'd seen a movie version as a kid, i couldn't remember ichabod's fate. and that's because all that's certain is that he goes missing on that blustery night, with only his horse and a smashed pumpkin left in his path. did he run away, filled with shame at being rejected at the dance? or did his rival follow him and scare him off? or did the headless horseman straight up kill him? i love how it remains a mystery, as many myths and folktales do. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span><br /></span>
